hands_on_practices.solution:
The symmetry operations are applied sequentially to the initial position vector $\vec{r}_0 = (x_0, y_0, z_0)$.

First, operation $\mathcal{O}_1$ consists of:
1. A counter-clockwise rotation by $90^\circ$ about the $z$-axis, represented by the matrix:
   $$
   R_z(90^\circ) = \begin{pmatrix}
   0 & -1 & 0 \\
   1 & 0 & 0 \\
   0 & 0 & 1
   \end{pmatrix}
   $$
   Applying this to $\vec{r}_0$:
   $$
   \begin{pmatrix}
   0 & -1 & 0 \\
   1 & 0 & 0 \\
   0 & 0 & 1
   \end{pmatrix}
   \begin{pmatrix}
   x_0 \\ y_0 \\ z_0
   \end{pmatrix}
   = \begin{pmatrix}
   -y_0 \\ x_0 \\ z_0
   \end{pmatrix}
   $$

2. A reflection through the $xy$-plane, represented by the matrix:
   $$
   M_{\text{ref}} = \begin{pmatrix}
   1 & 0 & 0 \\
   0 & 1 & 0 \\
   0 & 0 & -1
   \end{pmatrix}
   $$
   Applying this to the result:
   $$
   \begin{pmatrix}
   1 & 0 & 0 \\
   0 & 1 & 0 \\
   0 & 0 & -1
   \end{pmatrix}
   \begin{pmatrix}
   -y_0 \\ x_0 \\ z_0
   \end{pmatrix}
   = \begin{pmatrix}
   -y_0 \\ x_0 \\ -z_0
   \end{pmatrix}
   $$
   Thus, $\vec{r}_1 = (-y_0, x_0, -z_0)$.

Second, operation $\mathcal{O}_2$ is an inversion through the origin, represented by the matrix:
$$
M_{\text{inv}} = \begin{pmatrix}
-1 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & -1 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & -1
\end{pmatrix}
$$
Applying this to $\vec{r}_1$:
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
-1 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & -1 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & -1
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
-y_0 \\ x_0 \\ -z_0
\end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix}
y_0 \\ -x_0 \\ z_0
\end{pmatrix}
$$
Thus, $\vec{r}_2 = (y_0, -x_0, z_0)$.

The scalar product $\vec{r}_0 \cdot \vec{r}_2$ is:
$$
\vec{r}_0 \cdot \vec{r}_2 = x_0 \cdot y_0 + y_0 \cdot (-x_0) + z_0 \cdot z_0 = x_0 y_0 - x_0 y_0 + z_0^2 = z_0^2
$$
